{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b9dc9c4b-dd10-42f0-89d2-ec0680c28bfa","content":"Here's the `mcp.json` configuration for VS Code agent mode using a stdio-based C# MCP server:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Place this file at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root.\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means VS Code communicates with the server over stdin/stdout.\n- If your server uses HTTP/SSE instead, change `type` to `\"sse\"` and provide a `\"url\"` instead of `command`/`args`.\n- After saving, use **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the VS Code command palette to verify the server is detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe2d33e3-f97b-468f-a970-69ee77b08ddf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure an `mcp.json` file to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me check their project to give accurate advice.","outputTokens":294},"id":"415139a2-bf0c-4011-a942-7b421e070fc0","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:54:04.730Z","parentId":"9c833bca-5742-430f-9394-b870e71d7cee"}
